        Doubling
        --------
        Doubling is done through the Doubling Cube. The Doubling Cube is
        a bigger Die (6 faces) having on each face: 2,4,8,16,32,64.
        When a new game starts, the Doubling Cube is placed right in the
        centre on either side of the board with 64 face up as shown
        in the diagram #1 below. You could start yours with a 1 instead of
        64. When the Cube is showing 1 it means that neither player
        has offered a double to his opponent and it also means that
        either player has the right to offer a double to his opponent.

        What is Doubling your opponent ?

        After a game has started, and at any stage of the game, if
        player #1 evaluates his position and feels that he has a much
        better chance to win the game, then he offers the Doubling Cube
        to player #2, by pushing the Cube towards his opponent,
        and changing the Cubes face up value to the next higher value,
        in this case, changing it to 2.

        If player #2 accepts the Cube then the game continues and the
        stakes are doubled. In other words a game is counted
        as 2 points. A gammon as 4 points and a backgammon as 6 points.
        Now, things start getting better for player #2, he rolls a few
        doubles etc and he feels that at this stage of the game his
        chances of winning the game are better then those of player #1.
        So he offers a double to player #1 by pushing the Cube towards
        player #1 with face up value showing 4. The same procedure is
        applied as above and so on. Players can Double each other until
        the face value shows 64.

        If player #2 refuses the Double then the game is over and the
        player #1 wins the face value of the Cube, in this case 1 point.
        And a new game starts. The Cube going back to the center with
        face-up value as 1.




